<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101581874898173>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101581874898173>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101581874898173>We made it to the MOON!</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101581874898173#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Sun, Mar 10th 10:54 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=122873><span id=Guru>Phreda the Hand</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>208 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I met Phanny in Rivervale, where she finally satisfied her obligation to Gapeers Johannis.&nbsp;&nbsp;He rewarded her (and Rainah's and Lemoni's and Zargoth's!) diligence by giving her a beautiful anklet.  She replaced her dingy, well-beaten scarab boots with the anklet, and stuck her foot out for me to see.  Phanny is especially glad that her feet are now free of the constrictive scarab shell.  We halflings are not the shoe-wearing type, but as a travelling warrior, I can't afford to forgo any type of armor for the mere sakes of comfort or tradition.<br><br>While I was doing a relatively poor job of gathering silks and pelts for Rainah, Phanny, clever girl that she is, figured out how to get to the moon.  She learned that a wizard spire in North Karana has been converted to a lunar teleportation device, and where we could find it.  The prospect of going to the moon was so exciting, we couldn't resist!  <br><br>I never knew those pretty white spires were wizard spires until that day.  We talked to a lady standing between them, and she gave us a stone to carry.  It looked just like a diamond, but was way too big to be genuine.  Soon the spires activated and everything went black!<br><br>Thump, we landed on a platform in a cavernous room.  We exited to a long hallway PACKED with people!  There were so many odd folks of all races milling around, Phanny had much difficulty walking to the other end.  <br><br>We saw several merchants with awnings attached to buildings, but they all told us they hated our type and wouldn't sell to us!  Pshaw!  Nobody ever said that to me before!  That was too bad, too, because some of them had really nice things for sale.  One merchant had beautiful robes, perfect for Lemoni's next birthday.  Oh well.<br><br>We eventually found the exit to Shadow Haven. (That's what the city is called, although a more fitting name would be &quot;Curmudgeon Haven!&quot;)  We overheard the guards call our destination &quot;Paludal Caverns.&quot;<br><br>The carved rock walls of Shadow Haven's outskirts turned dark and mossy.  After a short distance it opened up to a huge cavern.  Below us we could see a camp of what looked like an rainbow coalition of thieves and miscreants - gnomes, halflings, humans, elves, and Vah Shir.  Thrilled with the opportunity laid out before us, Phanny and I gave a hoot and dived in!<br><br>The thieves, catburglars (who really were cats!), demogogues and pickpockets turned out to be worthy opponents.  We met and formed a group with an elf ranger named Foddaman McFodda.  He was just a little bit older than us, and let us do all the looting!   That was very generous of him, especially since the loot consisted of nice bronze armor and weapons.  Like Highpass, the place was hopping.  We barely had a moment's rest from one bad guy to the next; often we were bombarded by two or three at once.<br><br>Only once did we suffer a casualty, and it was me.  There were just too many burglars, not to mention an owlbear (what strange creatures they are!)  Once conscious, I limped back half naked to where my comrades were nursing their wounds.  After gathering my stuff, I said, &quot;cheer up! have some beer!&quot;  and handed Foddaman four short ales.  <br><br>He drank them all immediately and started jabbering incoherently.  I thought he was speaking Elf to us, but Phanny laughed and said he was too drunk to talk!  He couldn't walk very well either.  That looked like fun, so I chugged my remaining four short ales and joined him in complete inebriation!<br><br>Three hours later, we were STILL drunk and talking like idiots.  Short ales last a long time, even with my considerable Biggles alcohol tolerance!  Phanny sat patiently and waited for us to regain the ability to walk straight.  We tested our sobriety by attacking a lone sensate reishi mushroom before we rejoined the thieves camp.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Mar 22 10:49:39 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br>Phreda Biggles, 46 Warrior <br>Inebriator for the Order of the Keg <br><a href=HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/journal.html?user=122873 target=_new>Tales of a Halfling Tank Girl</a></td></td></tr>
