	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101156401616905>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101156401616905>What a time we had!</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101156401616905#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Sun, Jan 20th 6:01 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=122873><span id=Guru>Phreda the Hand</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>208 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I was all gung-ho about going down the Runnyeye stairs (as I am gung ho about visiting any new area) until Phanny reminded me of a shaken elf we met last year in the Gorge of King Xorbb.&nbsp;&nbsp;He asked us to help him retrieve his corpse from lower Runnyeye.  Although dressed in tatters, we could tell he was a much more experienced adventurer than either of us.  It seemed obvious to me that the goblins who killed him would consider us more vulnerable prey!  Phanny, bless her soul, instantly agreed to assist him.  I whispered in her ear that it would mean certain death for us but told the elf I would go too.  Luckily someone more qualified passed by and offered to retrieve the corpse for him.<br><br>Instead we ran through the Gorge and a bit of Karana to the West gate of Highpass Hold.  Soon after we arrived, Phanny received an invitation to join a group on the other end of the Hold.  Sounded good to me - I was kind of tired of the gnolls!  Soon a slightly familiar halfling named Potas appeared, cast Spirit of Wolf on us, and led us through the mountainous trail to his group.<br><br>I could not believe my eyes when we approached.  The scene was incredible!  Three tall folk - a human, a barbarian, and a troll, were up to their knees in orc bodies.  There must have been more than a dozen corpses staining the ground!  The barbarian was sharpening the largest sword I ever saw, and I think the troll was picking his butt.  I gawked for a less than a minute before more orcs appeared, brandishing rapiers and yelling obscenities at them.  Not wanting to appear cowardly, I immediately jumped into the sea of orc bodies and started clawing.<br><br>Formal introductions took longer than normal; they were continually interrupted by skirmishes.  Phanny and I quickly established our value to the group - me with my sharp, agile claws, and Phanny with her skillful, timely mending.  The height and number of comrades made melee much more challenging!  The orcs also liked to stand on steep rocks, which made them harder to reach.  Because of that, on more than one occasion I had the misfortune of standing directly under the troll.  Even with a warrior's constitution I reeled from the unintentional view of his underpants.  Bleah!<br><br>There was one more fellow in the area, a very noble looking dark elf.  I think he was a necromancer; he had a skeleton at his bidding, and he cast a special spell upon each of us which made us walk like ghosts. It felt kind of like swimming through the air! I had a lot of fun running up the steep incline of the mountainside to gain altitude, then floating over the heads of my party members.  The spell helped us reach the orcs on the rocks, since we didn't need the rocks to stay at their altitude.  Both the dark elf and his skeleton waited on the clifftops above us, awaiting a particular orc.   We honored him by agreeing to save that orc for him.  Between fights, Akronz (the dark elf) would flirt with me!  Between his innuendo and Phanny's teasing, I was blushing half the night!  He was admittedly darn good looking for an elf, but  I knew he was WAY out of my league.  I'm just a scruffy tomboy Hobbit girl.  He seemed like he could tangle with the gods.<br><br>Phanny and I stayed for quite a while.  It was a coveted location - the orcs swarmed us!  Our group turned out to be a most pleasant one.  What a motley crew we were!  Potas was a halfling Druid fellow, who knew Highpass Hold like the back of his hand.  Faethor was a quiet human with a creepy eyepatch. He had a funny way of giving the orcs big smiles as he ran his sword through their torsoes.  Arkainnen was the Barbarian with a sword as tall as me.  Of all of us, he dealt the most impressive blows, and had the most impressive hat - a wolf's head!  His face poked out of its mouth, hee hee!  And Banaz was the troll, a warrior from the looks of it.  I keep ragging on him, but he was quite the gentleman (as much as any troll could hope to be).  </p>&nbsp;<br>Phreda Biggles, 46 Warrior <br>Inebriator for the Order of the Keg <br><a href=HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/journal.html?user=122873 target=_new>Tales of a Halfling Tank Girl</a></td></td></tr>
