<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101098395743499>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101098395743499>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101098395743499>Dog-men beware!</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=122873&mid=101098395743499#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Sun, Jan 13th 11:52 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=122873><span id=Guru>Phreda the Hand</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>208 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>We were welcomed at the entrance to Highpass by a human knight and his assistant.&nbsp;&nbsp;He offered to accompany us to the city for a fee.  We would have agreed to that arrangement, but he wouldn't be leaving for another three hours.  Phanny and I were too impatient to wait that long!  So we continued without his assistance.<br><br>The plains turned rocky, and the path became narrow.  We had to step carefully, for we were walking up the side of the tallest mountain I had ever seen.  At one point while Phanny rested, I peered over the edge of the path.  Such a long drop to the bottom!  Dizziness hit me so suddenly, I squealed and backed away.  Further up, we saw an impossibly huge carving in the rock face, of a human god lounging between two columns.  Indeed, the whole area was so big and expansive it made me feel... insignificant. <br><br>Eventually we reached a doorway carved into the rock.  As we crossed the threshold, a tall dog-like creature jumped out in front of us - and started casting spells!  We weren't sure we would survive, but managed to kill him.  Then four more of the creatures attacked us!  Phanny yelled &quot;RUN!&quot; and ran deeper into the narrow, rocky path.  The beasts followed her, and I tried my best to taunt them while keeping track of where she was going.  We were in the middle of a giant maze, and didn't know what would be at the end of it. <br><br>Left and right she ran, slowing with each strike from the monsters.  Finally she saw what looked like human guards, and ran toward them.  But she didn't survive.  The guards swarmed her killers, and beat them all down.  I sat on the steps of the human stronghold next to her sad little corpse, and awaited her return.   Overhearing the guards, I learned that those beasts were called gnolls, and that the humans hated them with a passion.  I don't blame them.  Those aggressive spellcasting dog-men killed my sister!<br><br>When Phanny came back, we entered the human city.  We sought the enchanter's guild in order to purchase two &quot;animation&quot; spells for our elf friends.  The city inside was just as maze-like as the mountains outside!  We ran around and around looking for the guild, occasionally crashing into each other.  At great length, Phanny found the guild.  By then, we were thoroughly sick of the place and wanted to leave.  But we didn't know the correct way back!<br><br>Just then a halfling ran past us.  Phanny flagged him down and asked him to show us the way out.  He pleasantly obliged, and nimbly led the way to where we were first accosted by the gnolls.  We didn't feel like going home just yet, so we stuck around.  Sure enough, a few more gnolls appeared to attack us, and we beat them both.<br><br>Maxam (the name of the nice halfling who helped us) was quite the seasoned warrior. He was hunting a particular upper-crust gnoll.  Don't know what his name was.  The other gnolls were merely an annoyance to Maxam, so he led them back for us to smite.  It was an amusing arrangement.   But the most wonderful thing he did was give me a new weapon.  Claws so sharp and menacing, the gnolls became mincemeat before our very eyes!   I shall store the club inherited from my father indefinitely.  These new claws really suit me.  Even Maxam admitted that my strikes now rivalled his.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Jan 17 14:33:20 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br>Phreda Biggles, 46 Warrior <br>Inebriator for the Order of the Keg <br><a href=HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/journal.html?user=122873 target=_new>Tales of a Halfling Tank Girl</a></td></td></tr>
	     <tr><td colspan=2 align=right class=mform id=fs8>0 Replies</td></tr>
	     </form></table><tr><td colspan=2><ul>
</td></ul></tr></table>
